Cougaar Peer-to-Peer model using the JXTA protocols
\par 
\par The objects included in this model reside in the package org.cougaar.microedition.p2p and have been developed and tested using JXTA version 39e (11-21-2001). 
\par 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\i\f1\fs28 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.1\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-576\li576\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx576\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin576\itap0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Theory of operation
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par The idea behind this peer-to-peer model is to make use of the open-source JXTA protocols (}{\field{\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK "http://www.jxta.org" }{{\*\datafield 
00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b02000000170000000d0000007700770077002e006a007800740061002e006f00720067000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b2a00000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e006a007800740061002e006f00720067002f000000}}}{\fldrslt {
\cs15\ul\cf2 www.jxta.org}}}{) to have Cougaar agents form and join peer-groups, communicate and share information, and, in general, collaborate on distributed problem solving. 
\par 
\par To facilitate the use of the JXTA protocols within Cougaar, several key objects have been developed to support basic P2P interactions within the Cougaar framework. The most crucial of these objects are P2PshareableObject and JXTAObjectSharePlugI
n, both described next.
\par 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\i\f1\fs28 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.2\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-576\li576\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx576\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin576\itap0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {P2PShareableObject
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par This object defines a Serializable abstract class. Any object that is derived from P2PShareableObject is automatically designated as an object that can be shared among agents (also known as peers) via the JXTAOb
jectSharePlugIn. Examples of this are Hypothesis objects in the org.cougaar.microedition.dmht package.
\par 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\i\f1\fs28 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.3\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-576\li576\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx576\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin576\itap0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {JXTAObjectSharePlugIn
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par This Cougaar plug-in serves as the main mechanism for P2P activity that includes peer discovery, peer group membership, message passing, and other activities related to JXTA protocols.
\par 
\par The JXTAObjectSharePlugin also defines the <domain> and <sharegroup> parameters. These parameters define a peer group that the agent may wish to belong to, presumably to collaborate on a problem with peers of the same objective. 
\par 
\par The <domain> parameter is a way to ignore most of the JXTA P2P traffic that one may encounter on a wide area network. The <sharegroup> is, for now, the peer group name that the peer is interested in joining and collaborating with on a particular problem. 

\par 
\par As a Cougaar PlugIn class, this object implements essential plug-in methods:
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs26 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.3.1\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {setupSubscription()
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
When this method is called, the plug-in initializes the agent as a JXTA peer in the default peer group (called netPeerGroup) and establishes itself (i.e., \'93this\'94) as a discoveryListener using the addDiscoveryListener(this) method. 
When this happens for the first time, the JXTA Configurator (see below) will pop up to set the peer information.
\par 
\par Finally, a thread is spawned that periodically requests remote advertisements from the JXTA peer group. In particular, this peer will be interested in peer group advertisements that are the one(s) it desires to join.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs26 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.3.2\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Execute
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Execute() is called when an instance of P2PShareableObject is published in any way to the agent\rquote 
s blackboard. If the agent has joined the desired <sharedgroup> peer group and has established connectivity to the group\rquote s prop
agation pipe, the plug-in will compose a JXTA pipe message containing the object and relay the information to all members of the peer group. 
\par 
\par There are other methods in the JXTAObjectSharePlugIn which define the plug-in as a JXTA peer:
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs26 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.3.3\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {discoveryEvent
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {As a discoveryListener, the agent will be
 notified when others publish relevant JXTA advertisements. When notified, the discoveryEvent() method will be invoked with a data argument. By deciphering the argument, the plug-in determines if the advertisement is relevant to its own role. 
\par 
\par The adverti
sements that are relevant include a peer group advertisement of name <sharegroup>. The agent is also interested in pipe advertisements of the same description. To understand how these advertisements are promulgated, refer to the GroupFacilitatorPlugIn. 

\par 
\par W
hen the relevant peer group advertisement is discovered, the agent/peer will attempt to join the group through the JXTA membership protocol. The agent then establishes the discovery listening on the new peer groups discovery service (vs. the netPeerGroup 
discovery service that was used initially)
\par 
\par When the relevant pipe advertisement is available, the agent/peer will attempt to establish an InputPipe and OutputPipe in order to receive and transmit messages to the other peers in the peer group. The agent use
s the output pipe to send a pipe message to the other peers. The agent also establishes itself as a pipe message listener using the JXTA pipe service method createInputPipe(pipeadv, this). 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs26 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.3.4\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PipeMsgEvent
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {As a pipe message listener, the JXTAObjectSharePlugIn
 will be notified when any message is available on the peer group\rquote 
s propagation pipe via the pipeMsgListener method. When this happens, the messages containing the P2PShareableObject are read and will be rehydrated and published to the local blackboard. 
\par 
\par Plug-ins interested on the local blackboard that have subscribed to any of the shareable objects will have the subscriptions fulfilled accordingly. In this way, the JXTAObjectSharePlugIn provides a way of sharing blackboard content amongst peers in a peer
 group.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\i\f1\fs28 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.4\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-576\li576\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx576\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin576\itap0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {GroupFacilitatorPlugIn
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par The GroupFacilitatorPlugIn was designed to manage the creation and formation of peer groups within the system. In any system of P2P Cougaar agents there should be at least one agent acting as group facilitator to coordinate this function.  
\par 
\par Since any peer can create and publish peer groups and related advertisements, the GroupFacilitatorPlugIn was invented to prevent the formation of multiple peer groups with the same name. JXTA identifies peer groups using a generated GUID a
nd does not prohibit the formation of multiple peer groups having the same name. It is the current understanding that two peers will create the same-named peer group simultaneously and each join the separate peer groups, though the names are the same.

\par 
\par To prevent multiple peer groups and the over proliferation, the GroupFacilitatorPlugIn starts JXTA identically to any other peer. It also establishes itself as a discoveryListener, examining discovery events for advertisements related to its role. 
\par 
\par The plug-in defines a <domain> parameter that it uses to flag peer advertisements. Any peer advertisement description that matches the <domain> string will be examined. Then the peer\rquote 
s share group requirements are analyzed. If it has not done so already, the facilitator will create the share group and publish it to everyone. The advertisement for this peer group is maintained on a local list of \'93facilitated groups\'94
 to prevent redundant peer group creation in the JXTA space. 
\par 
\par Once the facilitator established the requested peer group, a pipe advertisement is also created and associated with the newly established peer group. This too is advertised to the group.
\par 
\par Finally, the advertisements published by the facilitator are given a specific lifetime. Using the discovery 
service, JXTA allows an advertisement to be published repeatedly (at a rate related to the lifetimeForOthers parameter) up until the second lifetime parameter. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {discovery.publish(peergroupadv, 
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 {DiscoveryService.GROUP, 
\par lifetime, lifetimeForOthers);
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par 
\par Usin
g lifetime parameters will inhibit extended caching of the peer group ads with any other peer on the network (i.e., well beyond the life of the process that was used to establish). If this is not done, one will see an accumulation of peer group advertisem
ents passed about the peer group even on subsequent runs of the system. This can be particularly irritating if it is desired to have and join one particular group or to start over for development purposes.
\par 
\par 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b\i\f1\fs28 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.5\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-576\li576\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx576\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin576\itap0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Peer Configuration and the JXTA Configurator
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Coug
aar agents that establish themselves as JXTA peers using either the JXTAObjectSharePlugIn or the GroupFacilitatorPlugIn will pop up the JXTA Configurator the first time they are run. This paragraph describes the essential elements of the configuration too
l and how they impact the Cougaar agent design. The configurator has several top level tabs: Basics, Advanced, Routers and Security.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b\f1\fs26 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1.5.1\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls1\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Basics
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
Every agent running as a peer must have a JXTA peer name. Specify an arbitrary but unique and meaningful peer name. 
\par 
\par One may optionally specify a proxy server but this can be left OFF. If behind a firewall, JXTA will use one of several hosts on the internet but this can be disables as well.
